  "prompt": "Cricket: Batsman strikes the ball, is caught by the bowler. But since the non-striker is a better batsman, and is out of his crease, the bowler removes the bails at the non- striker end and appeals for run-out. He does not appeal for caught and bowled. Which batsmen is legally out and why?",
  "response": "In this scenario, the batsman who was caught by the bowler is legally out. Here's the explanation:\n\n1. Caught and Bowled:\n- When a batsman is caught by the bowler before the ball touches the ground, it is a valid dismissal.\n- In this case, the batsman who was caught by the bowler would be out \"caught and bowled\" according to the cricket rules.\n\n2. Run-out Situation:\n- The non-striker being out of his crease does not automatically make him out.\n- The bowler would need to appeal for run-out, which he did not do in this scenario.\n\n3. Dismissal Priority:\n- If a batsman is caught, this dismissal takes precedence over a potential run-out.\n- Even if the non-striker is out of his crease, the caught dismissal would be enforced first.\n\nTherefore, the batsman who was caught by the bowler is legally out, ruled as \"caught and bowled\". The non-striker remains not out, as no run-out appeal was made, and the caught dismissal takes precedence.",
